result.execSummary:
The defendant Terrell Montez Nash was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Flee Or Elude An Officer, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(3).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

 Appellate Rights given

Defendant Terrell Montez Nash in court with attorney Vincent Paul Guimont.  Stephan Eduard Nolten appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Case in court for a Plea and Sentencing.  Parties have reached a resolution in this matter. State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law.
Court is in receipt Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum.  Negotiations placed on the record and confirmed by defense counsel and defendant.
 
PLEA HEARING PROCEEDED: 

AS TO COUNT 1:  
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.   
Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  
Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored. Court orders defendant provide a DNA sample.
Defendant appeared later in the morning by zoom and was given new court date.

Attorney Mary Guimont on behalf of Vincent Paul Guimont in court.  Alexandria S. Carlson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Case in Court for a Scheduling Conference. Defendant's apprearence waived. Defense requested an ajournment. Parties pre-selected next date. Case adjourned in Branch 45.
Pursuant to Chief Judge Directive 22-04, parties are hereby notified that as of July 30, 2022, this case will be assigned to Branch 6, Judge Ellen Brostrom, in Room 608 of the Courthouse.

Attorney Vince Guimont contacted the Court and State via email regarding Plea/Sentencing hearing scheduled for July 7, 2022 at 04:00 pm. 
Attorney Vince Guimont recently took over this case from Attorney Darryl Smith. 
Attorney Vince Guimont is not available for Plea/Sentencing hearing scheduled for July 7, 2022. 
Parties will appear via Zoom Video Conference on July 7, 2022 at 10:45 am to reschedule hearing.
